```
workspace = {
        didChangeWatchedFiles = {
          dynamicRegistration = false
        }
      }
```

Is the best workaround

> ```
> workspace = {
>         didChangeWatchedFiles = {
>           dynamicRegistration = false
>         }
>       }
> ```
> 
> Is the best workaround

And just to be sure: This should be added to the client's capabilities in my LSP configuration right (together where I set `on_attach` etc)?

@lewis6991 I tried your snippet and had a lot of exception on `  local d = vim.split(data, '%s+')` about `data` being `null`.

I added a test and now I have no problem anymore, but `fswatch` does not seem to run for my project (using haskell-language-server), but it runs perfectly for another project (using nil LSP), so that's a huge progress.

And it does not eat my CPU anymore.

> Could some of the people who had performance problems try with #26108 ?

After updating to latest neovim nightly (by using ppa http://ppa.launchpad.net/neovim-ppa/unstable/ubuntu - `0.10.0~ubuntu1+git202312032103-988b472d9-c60402a16-d6245ab7f~ubuntu22.04.1`) this still seems to be an issue. Using Ubuntu Jammy with tons of files (In total 90k files ` find -type f | wc -l` Why so many? ~40k git-ignored assets, ~40k build/tmp cache files/log files, node_modules etc.) blocks down the editor completely during first LSP initialization - `workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles` accord. to debug log:

```
[TRACE][2023-12-04 14:00:40] ...lsp/handlers.lua:636    "default_handler"       "client/registerCapability"     {  ctx = '{
  client_id = 2,
  method = "client/registerCapability"
}',
result = {
  registrations = { {       
     id = "7fb42980-7e09-4f60-920e-ecfa867acce6",        
     method = "workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles",        
     registerOptions = {          
        watchers = { {              
           globPattern = "**/*.{js,cjs,mjs,ts,cts,mts,jsx,tsx,json,vue}"            
} } } } } } }
[DEBUG][2023-12-04 14:00:50] .../vim/lsp/rpc.lua:380    "server_request: callback result"       
  {  result = vim.NIL,  status = true}
``` 

-> takes 10 seconds for us.

The ppa version seems to include the git commit from the MR, so that seemed not to solve the problem.

Applying the workaround of disabling watchfiles removes the 10 second delay after the first file open.
Especially noticeable with Volar (Vue) and Tailwind LSPs for us.

Just tested on a Raspberry PI 5 with a SD Card:

```
Took 175.463502ms to setup 1519 watchers for: /path/to/changedfilespy/changedfilespy
Took 262.90266ms to setup 1519 watchers for: /path/to/changedfilespy/changedfilespy
Took 43.547496ms to setup 262 watchers for: /usr/lib/python3.11
```

Not sure why I'm seeing less watchers here, but what's interesting is that we're setting them up twice due to the payload from the server.
We can probably de-duplicate that.

```
 registerOptions = {
              watchers = { {
                  globPattern = "**/pyrightconfig.json",
                  kind = 7
                }, {
                  globPattern = "**",
                  kind = 7
                }, {
                  globPattern = {
                    baseUri = "file:///usr/lib/python3.11",
                    pattern = "**"
                  },
                  kind = 7
                } }
```


> I don't think smoothing this out over the event loop is going to help at all.

Why not? It's a one time cost after the server starts up.

The only alternative I can think off is offloading it to a thread, but I'm not sure how we can get that to work. I saw there's support for `uv.new_thread`, but afaik it cannot return a table with events handles.
So we'd have to off-load the entire watcher functionality, and communicate similarly to how the `fswatch` integration works.


> When I said it choked my M1 Pro, I really meant it brought it to a stop and made Nvim completely unresponsive; much much longer than 100ms.

You mention an NFS mount before, was that with the project being on the NFS mount?

> Some things we could further improve on:
> 
>     * De-duplicate debounce (`_watchfiles` has it's own mechanism)
> 
>     * Global file-path based watcher de-duplication. (I think currently using two clients would end up having each client register their own watchers)
> 
>     * Deal with watcher limits (`proc/sys/fs/inotify/max_user_watches`)
> 
>     * Configuration for excludes? From my testing it looks like there are a lot of folders watched that wouldn't need to be. See https://github.com/search?q=watcherExclude&type=code

Another optimization can be for static file paths (no special symbols in pattern). For example nil_ls wants to watch only two files, but neovim is scanning the entire nixpkgs repository (1-2 seconds on my PC), in the end only one watch is set.

```lua
    capabilities = {
      ["workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles"] = { {
          id = "workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles",
          method = "workspace/didChangeWatchedFiles",
          registerOptions = {
            watchers = { {
                globPattern = "/nix/store/zyzhqfys86byv201frlpiyipzzw38p02-source/flake.lock"
              }, {
                globPattern = "/nix/store/zyzhqfys86byv201frlpiyipzzw38p02-source/flake.nix"
              } }
          }
        } }
    }
```

Also maybe some patterns, like `**` and `**/filename`, can be treated specially, like checking only for excludes during directory walking (need to setup watches on all directories, except excluded like .git). De-duplication is needed for single language server too. For example pyright wants to watch `**/pyrightconfig.json` and `**`. It results in double directory walking.
